Below is a basic solution. It helps to visualise the problem before solving it. You start at the first row, on the first column. You only want to change rows once the column has been filled with all values. The outer for loop controls the rows, and the inner for loop controls the columns.


&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    var n = 3;
    var counter  = 1;
    var outerArray = [];

    // Now just add to the array with a nested for loop
    for(var i = 0; i &lt; n; i++) {
        // Add empty array to the outer array.
        outerArray.push([]);
        // outer for loop steps through the rows
        for(var j = 0; j &lt; n; j++) {
            // The inner loop steps through the columns
            outerArray[i][j] = counter;
            counter++;
        }
      }
    // Now just print the array.
    console.log(outerArray);

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    function printTable(n) {
    	let i, j;
    let a = [];
    let counter = 0;
    for (i = 0; i &lt; n; i ++) {
        a[i] = [];
        for (j = 0; j &lt; n; j ++) {
    			counter++
            a[i][j] = counter;
        }
    }
    console.log(a);
    }
    printTable(4)


&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

Thanks guys! Modified it and figured it out

